Here's the pattern using a custom `Window` subclass and `Preferences`:

**App.xaml.cs** — return a custom window that hooks lifecycle events:

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
        => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
}
```

**AppWindow.cs** — save on background/destroy, restore on resume:

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
        SaveDraft();
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
        {
            notePage.RestoreDraft();
        }
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        if (Page is AppShell shell
            && shell.CurrentPage is NotePage notePage)
        {
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", notePage.GetDraftText());
        }
    }
}
```

**NotePage.xaml.cs** — expose save/restore helpers:

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        RestoreDraft(); // also restore on first launch
    }

    public string GetDraftText() => DraftEditor.Text ?? string.Empty;

    public void RestoreDraft()
    {
        DraftEditor.Text = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }
}
```

### Key points

| Concern | Why |
|---|---|
| Save in **both** `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying` | Android's back button can skip `Stopped` and go straight to `Destroying` |
| Use `Preferences` (not a DB) | Lifecycle handlers must complete in **1–2 seconds** to avoid ANR/watchdog kills |
| Restore in `OnResumed` **and** the constructor | `Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch — only after a `Stopped` → foreground transition |

If you're using MVVM, the same logic applies — just read/write your ViewModel's `DraftText` property instead of touching the control directly.
